      sampleAnswer: "Social media has revolutionized the way people communicate, share information, and engage with the world around them. Platforms such as those enabling instant messaging, content sharing, and live streaming have broken down geographical barriers and given ordinary individuals a voice on a global stage. News travels faster than ever, and social movements can mobilize supporters across continents within hours. However, these benefits come with significant drawbacks. The spread of misinformation has become a critical concern, as algorithms designed to maximize engagement often amplify sensational and divisive content. This contributes to political polarization and erodes trust in established institutions and media outlets. Cyberbullying and privacy violations are additional consequences that disproportionately affect young users. To mitigate these issues, social media platforms must implement more transparent content moderation policies and invest in systems that can detect and limit the spread of false information. Users themselves should cultivate media literacy and exercise critical judgment when consuming online content. While the drawbacks of social media are undeniable, its capacity to connect communities and democratize information suggests that the benefits can outweigh the risks if responsible measures are adopted by both platforms and users.",
