      vocabulary: ["ethical dilemma", "alternatives", "humane", "regulatory", "welfare", "biomedical", "in-vitro", "advocacy"],
      sampleAnswer: "Animal testing has long been a cornerstone of biomedical research and pharmaceutical development, primarily because living organisms provide complex biological systems that cannot be fully replicated in laboratory settings. Proponents argue that animal testing has contributed to life-saving vaccines, surgical techniques, and treatments for conditions ranging from cancer to heart disease. Nevertheless, the ethical arguments against animal testing are compelling. Animals used in experiments frequently endure significant pain and suffering, raising questions about whether the ends truly justify the means. Critics contend that sentient beings deserve moral consideration and that subjecting them to invasive procedures for human benefit is fundamentally unjust. Fortunately, advances in technology have produced viable alternatives. In-vitro testing using human cell cultures, computational modeling, and organ-on-a-chip technology can replicate biological processes with increasing accuracy. While these methods cannot yet replace animal testing entirely, they represent a promising trajectory toward more humane scientific practices. Governments should implement stricter regulations that mandate the use of alternatives wherever they are available and invest in research to develop new substitution methods. A gradual and systematic transition away from animal testing, guided by both scientific rigor and ethical commitment, is both achievable and necessary.",
